COVID-19 Model Iteration 2 Endogeneity Evaluation

The code for the assessment of endogeneity using the Gaussian Copula approach comes from

Hult, G. T. M., J. F. Hair, D. Proksch, M. Sarstedt, A. Pinkwart, & C. M. Ringle (2018). Addressing Endogeneity in International Marketing Applications of Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling. Journal of International Marketing, 26(3), 1–21. https://doi.org/10.1509/jim.17.0151

Test of non-normality

The Gaussian Copula approach can only be used if the independent variable in question is non-normally distributed.

# Find out if independent (i.e., exogenous) variables are non-normally distributed
# If yes, Gaussian Copula approach can be used.
#Distrusting Beliefs
shapiro.test(model$construct_scores[,"Distrusting Beliefs"])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  model$construct_scores[, "Distrusting Beliefs"]
## W = 0.95037, p-value = 7.641e-11
lillie.test(model$construct_scores[,"Distrusting Beliefs"])
## 
##  Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) normality test
## 
## data:  model$construct_scores[, "Distrusting Beliefs"]
## D = 0.053715, p-value = 0.004631
ggplot(as.data.frame(model$construct_scores), aes(`Distrusting Beliefs`)) +
  geom_density()

# Knowledge
shapiro.test(model$construct_scores[,"Knowledge"])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  model$construct_scores[, "Knowledge"]
## W = 0.94065, p-value = 4.246e-12
lillie.test(model$construct_scores[,"Knowledge"])
## 
##  Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) normality test
## 
## data:  model$construct_scores[, "Knowledge"]
## D = 0.19294, p-value < 2.2e-16

All independent (or endogenous) variables are non-normally distributed. Therefore, the Gaussian Copula approach can be used for all of them.

Regression of Response Beliefs on Distrusting Beliefs and Knowledge

# Define Variables for easy access
KN <- model$construct_scores[,"Knowledge"]
DI <- model$construct_scores[,"Distrusting Beliefs"]
RB <- model$construct_scores[,"Response Beliefs"]

# Define number of bootstraps: 10.000 for reporting, 100 for testing
bootrounds <- 10000

# Estimate regression model
rbmodel <- lm(RB ~ DI + KN)
summary(rbmodel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = RB ~ DI + KN)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.39484 -0.38545  0.01552  0.42372  2.09253 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  6.195e-17  3.239e-02   0.000  1.00000    
## DI          -7.009e-01  3.414e-02 -20.531  < 2e-16 ***
## KN           1.075e-01  3.414e-02   3.148  0.00176 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.6724 on 428 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5499, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5478 
## F-statistic: 261.5 on 2 and 428 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
bootrb <- Boot(rbmodel, R=bootrounds)
## Loading required namespace: boot
summary(bootrb)
## 
## Number of bootstrap replications R = 10000 
##                original   bootBias   bootSE     bootMed
## (Intercept)  6.1953e-17 0.00037303 0.032452  0.00050357
## DI          -7.0091e-01 0.00047605 0.037875 -0.70197304
## KN           1.0748e-01 0.00011589 0.035094  0.10686888
# Make base df
rbdf <- data.frame(Construct = c("Distrusting Beliefs", "Knowledge", "Copula Distrusting Beliefs", "Copula Knowledge"), 
                   Original.Model.Value = c(summary(bootrb)[2:3,5],NA,NA),
                   Original.Model.p = c(bootSig(model$data, bootrb, 2, 0)[2:3],NA,NA)
)

# Calculate copulas for independent variables
KN_star <- createCopula(KN)
DI_star <- createCopula(DI)


# Calculate results with copula for Distrusting Beliefs
# Input is regular model + copula + 0
copuladirb <- lm(RB ~ DI + KN + DI_star + 0)
summary(copuladirb)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = RB ~ DI + KN + DI_star + 0)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.41391 -0.39032  0.01102  0.41530  2.14875 
## 
## Coefficients:
##         Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## DI      -0.87618    0.12199  -7.182 3.06e-12 ***
## KN       0.10353    0.03415   3.032  0.00258 ** 
## DI_star  0.15775    0.10544   1.496  0.13535    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.6707 on 428 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5523, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5491 
## F-statistic:   176 on 3 and 428 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# Bootstrap Standard Errors
bootcopuladirb <- Boot(copuladirb, R=bootrounds)
summary(bootcopuladirb)
## 
## Number of bootstrap replications R = 10000 
##         original   bootBias   bootSE  bootMed
## DI      -0.87618 -0.0084328 0.159081 -0.88677

## DI_star  0.15775  0.0102387 0.139431  0.16491
# Calculate corrected p-values based on bootstrapped standard errors
# Input is data, bootstrapped results, number of independent variables, number of copulas
bootSig(model$data, bootcopuladirb, 2,1)
## [1] 6.290132e-08 3.658321e-03 2.585228e-01
# Attach to df
rbdf <- rbdf %>% cbind(
  DI.Co.Model.Value = c(summary(bootcopuladirb)[1:3,5], NA),
  DI.Co.Model.p = c(bootSig(model$data, bootcopuladirb, 2,1), NA)
)

Neither the Distrusting Beliefs nor the Knowledge Copula is significant, indicating that there is no hidden endogeneity in the regression of Response Beliefs on its predictors.

In looking only at single copulas, none of copulas achieves a significant p-value. However, when combining multiple copulas, the copula for Response Beliefs achieves a significant p-value in some cases (p < 0.1). Further, adding the single copula increases the path coefficient by 0.057 from 0.488 in the original model to 0.545. Both of this indicates that Response Beliefs might be endogenous. There is nothing pointing to hidden endogeneity in any of the other predictors.

As the capula cannot be integrated in iterative model improvement, the capula test will be repeated for the final models.
